{{short description|Montain on the border of Montenegro and Albania}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} {{Infobox mountain | name = Zla Kolata | other_name = | photo = Zla Kolata.JPG | photo_caption = Zla Kolata from northeast | elevation_m = 2534 | elevation_ref = <ref name="pb">[http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=30157 "Maja Kolata" on Peakbagger] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170722121626/http://peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=30157 |date=22 July 2017 }} Retrieved 27 September 2011</ref> | prominence_m = | prominence_ref = | listing = [[List of countries by highest point|Country high point]] | map = Montenegro | map_size = 220 | map_caption = Zla Kolata in Montenegro (on Albania border) | label_position = left | location = [[Montenegro]] / [[Albania]] border | range = [[Prokletije]], [[Dinaric Alps]] | coordinates = {{coord|42|29|06|N|19|53|50|E|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = <ref name="pb" /> | age = | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }}
'''Zla Kolata''' ([[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]]: Зла Колата, ''Zla Kolata''; {{lang-sq|Kollata e Keqe}}) is a mountain of the [[Prokletije]] on the [[Border crossings of Albania|border]] of [[Montenegro]] and [[Albania]].<ref>[http://www.summitpost.org/kolac-kolata/155151 summitpost.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126145517/http://www.summitpost.org/kolac-kolata/155151 |date=26 January 2018 }} Summitpost claims incorrectly that this peak lies entirely within Montenegro. Retrieved 27 September 2011</ref>
== Description == Zla Kolata has an elevation of {{convert|2534|m|ft|0}}, making it the highest mountain in Montenegro, and the 16th highest in Albania.<ref name="Crolla McKeating 2014 p. 241">{{cite book | last = Crolla | first = R. | last2 = McKeating | first2 = C. | title = Europe's High Points: Reaching the summit of every country in Europe | publisher = Cicerone Press | year = 2014 | isbn = 978-1-84965-960-4 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=mVVOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT241 | access-date = 3 September 2018 | page = 241 }}</ref><ref name="Abraham 2018 p. 87">{{cite book | last = Abraham | first = R. | title = The Peaks of the Balkans Trail: Montenegro, Albania and Kosovo | publisher = Cicerone Press | year = 2018 | isbn = 978-1-78362-556-7 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ouBTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT87 | access-date = 3 September 2018 | page = 87 }}</ref> It is located on the border of the [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]] municipality of Montenegro and the [[Tropojë]] district of [[Kukës County]], Albania. Zla Kolata has an enormous summit and is a popular tourist destination in both countries. Standing half a kilometer to the northeast at {{convert|2528|m|ft|0}}, only slightly lower, is [[Kolata e Mirë]] or [[Kolata e Mirë|Dobre Kolata]] , also located on the [[Border crossings of Albania|border]]. The highest peak on this massif is a kilometer east-southeast of Zla Kolata and is completely on Albanian soil; called [[Rodi e Kollatës]] or [[Rodi e Kollatës|Maja e Kollatës]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.westcoastpeaks.com/Peaks/kolata.html | title = Retrieved 19 January 2017 | access-date = 3 September 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150111062408/http://www.westcoastpeaks.com/Peaks/kolata.html | archive-date = 11 January 2015 | dead-url = no | df = }}</ref> it rises to 2,552&nbsp;m (8,373&nbsp;ft) but despite the dramatic views into the [[Valbona Valley]], is not as often visited.
